WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.880
My name is Wei, and I'm here together with Kiegan, who is down there getting mic'd up.

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:18.000
And today we're going to talk to you about bees.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.000
So bees.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.959
We think our users have a lot in common with bees.

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:28.400
For one thing, we share a love of hexagons.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:31.480
But more importantly, bees are pollinators.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:39.279
And what we know is that the pollinator population is really important to the health of an ecosystem.

00:00:39.279 --> 00:00:44.200
And I just noticed we have this beautiful backdrop behind us with these really nice

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.200
butterflies.

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:52.439
So we didn't plan this, but it's kind of appropriate.

00:00:52.439 --> 00:00:58.480
And what we hope to convince you of by the end of our talk is that, like bees, our users

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:05.879
can enrich their own data ecosystem with effort and empathy.

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:09.160
So what do we mean by data ecosystem?

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:14.000
And to explain, I think it's going to be helpful to tell you a bit about ourselves.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:15.839
So Kiegan and I work at NOC.

00:01:15.839 --> 00:01:19.599
We are a nonpartisan social research organization.

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:25.559
And at NOC, our coworkers, our partners, our clients, we work on, we use different

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:31.400
types of software, so SAS, Excel, Stata.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:33.239
And we produce lots of documentation.

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:38.559
So policy briefs, technical reports, data code books, and we do that in a variety of

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:42.360
formats like Word and PDF.

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:51.120
We work with expert coders, non-coders, and everyone in between.

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:57.879
As our users and developers, we have to leave the hive and we have to interact with all

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:01.480
these people in our ecosystem.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:08.080
And to do so, I think we're very lucky to have all these great tools that folks in our

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:13.800
community have built to help to facilitate these interactions.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:16.399
So that's what we mean by an ecosystem.

00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:23.360
It's a diverse environment where we have folks with a range of skills using different types

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:28.679
of software and creating different kinds of products.

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:35.679
Why do we feel so strongly about enriching this data ecosystem?

00:02:35.679 --> 00:02:41.000
Well, three reasons.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.020
So in our work, we either succeed or we fail together.

00:02:46.020 --> 00:02:53.399
So if our work is late or we bust our budget, the client is not going to care that our team

00:02:53.399 --> 00:03:00.100
did this or the SAS team didn't do that or manual review took two weeks longer than expected.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:06.000
So it's really important for us to make sure that everybody succeeds, whether we're a SAS

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.679
user or a Stata user or a non-coder.

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:18.759
The second thing is, well, as our users, we do better work when others do better work.

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:23.839
So it really helps us when others thrive.

00:03:23.839 --> 00:03:30.880
And the third thing is that the more we can lower the barrier to R for non-R users and

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:38.160
beginner R users, and the more we can show that R not only works with other software,

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:42.880
but it also works for other software, then it's easier for us to convince our bosses

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:48.919
to invest in the infrastructure and the support to support R and other open source software

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:54.839
and also to pay for us to come to this conference next year.

00:03:54.839 --> 00:04:01.880
So that's why we care so much about enriching the ecosystem.

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:09.240
Before we dive into how to be a pollinator, so just one word about what we mean by empathy.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:15.119
When we work in an ecosystem, we quickly realize that different people have different ways

00:04:15.119 --> 00:04:17.760
of thinking about the world.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.720
And biologists have a word for it.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:25.500
It's called unveiled, and an unveiled is an animal's perceptual world.

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:29.720
So every species senses the world in a different way.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:37.399
So two species sharing the same physical environment have completely different experiences of the

00:04:37.399 --> 00:04:38.399
same environment.

00:04:38.559 --> 00:04:46.679
So bats and whales, for example, they hear the world in a way that human beings do not.

00:04:46.679 --> 00:04:48.119
Here is where empathy comes in.

00:04:48.119 --> 00:04:54.000
So among all the species, humans are unique in that we have a capacity to appreciate the

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.279
unveiling of other species.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:05:02.359
So in our context, empathy means being able to perceive code and perceive data in a way

00:05:02.359 --> 00:05:08.239
that other people do.

00:05:09.079 --> 00:05:13.600
Now, Kege and I are going to share with you three lessons we've learned on how to be a

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:14.600
pollinator.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:17.399
And the first lesson is do no harm.

00:05:17.399 --> 00:05:22.480
As R users and developers, it's really important for us to be really careful and intentional

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:30.040
when we interact with others in our ecosystem and when we deal with foreign data formats.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:37.160
So here is one example of reading data from Stata into R. And they say that the lessons

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.399
that stick with you most are the ones you learn from your mistakes.

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:43.040
And so this is one that's very dear to my heart.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:48.200
Anyways, this example comes from the General Social Survey, or the GSS.

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:53.119
And the GSS is one of the most widely cited studies of American society.

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:58.299
It's a study that's been run by NOC for the past 50 years.

00:05:58.299 --> 00:06:02.399
And here we have an entry from the GSS codebook.

00:06:02.399 --> 00:06:07.880
This variable describes the number of educations received by the respondent's mother.

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:15.239
And the codebook tells us what the unique values of this variable is and number of cases

00:06:15.239 --> 00:06:16.239
with each value.

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:19.399
And then at the bottom, we have this section called reserved codes.

00:06:19.399 --> 00:06:21.160
And these are missing values.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.420
So there are three different types of missing values.

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:30.359
And we have 316 cases that are missing value because they said they don't know.

00:06:30.359 --> 00:06:35.000
And then we have 100 cases that are missing values because they said that they did not

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.600
grow up with a female caregiver growing up.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:40.519
So they were not asked this question.

00:06:40.519 --> 00:06:46.519
Now when we read this Stata data file into R, we see that the three different missing

00:06:46.519 --> 00:06:51.000
value types have been collapsed into a single NA.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.279
And this looks bad, right?

00:06:52.279 --> 00:06:55.279
Because it looks like we've just lost information.

00:06:55.279 --> 00:06:59.320
So why does this happen?

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:04.799
If folks are familiar with SAS or Stata, it's that whereas these two software have

00:07:04.799 --> 00:07:09.679
extended missing types so they can support multiple missing value types, R only has a

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:12.160
single system missing.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.399
So what do we do about this?

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:20.480
Well, it turns out that the R data object that we have, whether we've read in the data

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:26.399
using Haven or we used the foreign package, the R data object still contains these missing

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:27.399
value types.

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:33.359
And it takes a little bit of effort and a few more lines of code to recover the different

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:34.359
types.

00:07:34.359 --> 00:07:39.480
Folks who are interested can see Haven's convergent semantics for more information.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:46.040
But our point here is that when you're working with a new or foreign data format, it really

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:52.200
is important to take a moment to learn about the idiosyncrasies of that specific format.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:56.200
And it's part of doing no harm.

00:07:56.200 --> 00:07:58.200
Here is another example.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:00.720
Here we have a screenshot of an Excel spreadsheet.

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:06.119
The contents don't really matter, but you can see that a few rows have been highlighted.

00:08:06.119 --> 00:08:10.600
So there is data in the formatting.

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:15.559
And these could be cases that have been flagged by a team for review.

00:08:15.559 --> 00:08:22.200
So some people have feelings about formatting as data.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:30.799
But our view is that this data can be important, and it's important that we preserve this data.

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:35.719
And the great thing about R is that there are these packages, openxlsx.xl, that really

00:08:35.719 --> 00:08:41.359
helps us to retain this information in a very easy way.

00:08:41.359 --> 00:08:47.440
And we should take the effort, a few lines of code to preserve this information.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:52.320
So the lesson here is it's going to take a bit of effort and a bit of empathy, but it's

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:57.119
really important as pollinators that we take care with other people's data and we do no

00:08:57.119 --> 00:08:58.119
harm.

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:01.000
So I'm going to turn it over to Keegan.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.359
All right.

00:09:02.359 --> 00:09:03.359
Can you hear me?

00:09:03.359 --> 00:09:04.359
Is my mic on?

00:09:04.359 --> 00:09:05.359
Awesome.

00:09:05.359 --> 00:09:06.359
Thank you.

00:09:06.359 --> 00:09:09.900
So the second principle of how to be a pollinator is to make things that just work.

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:14.400
So what we really mean by this is we want to remove barriers for either people interacting

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:19.479
with R or people who are using things that we're creating in R to make it so that things

00:09:19.479 --> 00:09:21.880
just work for them.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:28.599
So a good example of making things that just work is consider how your data are being outputted.

00:09:28.599 --> 00:09:33.340
So you might take the usual approach of I'm going to share this data that I've cleaned

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:35.880
and wrangled in R. It's really awesome looking.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:36.880
It's tidy.

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:39.500
I'm going to save it out as a CSV.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:41.239
So that's one approach.

00:09:41.239 --> 00:09:45.880
If you think about who the next user is going to be, you could also take a different approach.

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:51.320
And again, with one line of code here, using the foreign package, we can write foreign

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.760
and include the command package equals SAS.

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:57.900
And that gives us a SAS script.

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:02.760
So now not only do we have the CSV, but the next person who uses this data, if they're

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:07.280
going to use it in SAS, they have a script that reads in the data and adds the correct

00:10:07.280 --> 00:10:10.679
formatting and labels for them automatically.

00:10:10.679 --> 00:10:16.440
So this is a really great way to make sure that the next person has an easier time.

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.760
They go ahead and run this script, and the data just works.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:24.320
They don't have to go digging for the formatting and the labels and reencode everything in

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:26.179
a way that makes sense to SAS.

00:10:26.179 --> 00:10:27.179
It just works.

00:10:27.179 --> 00:10:30.700
It's already there.

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:36.059
Another example is something you've maybe run into, a message like this.

00:10:36.059 --> 00:10:37.239
Looks like there's a hiccup.

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:41.299
The server-hosted dashboard is not filtering based on the uploaded file, but it's working

00:10:41.299 --> 00:10:42.840
on my local computer.

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:46.780
So maybe you've gotten this message, this panicked email.

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:49.580
Maybe you've sent this panicked email at some point.

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:52.099
It's working on one computer, but it's not working on another.

00:10:52.099 --> 00:10:54.679
It's working on the server, but it's not working locally.

00:10:54.679 --> 00:10:59.400
So for somebody who's not super confident in figuring out when errors are going wrong,

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:01.599
this can be really scary.

00:11:01.599 --> 00:11:05.200
This can be a way that they're interacting with R that they don't know what is going

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:07.460
wrong and how to fix it.

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:13.159
So we can remove this possible barrier by, from the start, using something like RENV.

00:11:13.159 --> 00:11:16.640
And there are a lot of different options, but essentially, if you don't know what RENV

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:18.640
is, go look it up.

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:23.320
But it allows us to keep track of the package versions we're using when we're writing and

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:29.559
implementing code and share those with any other people or environments that we're going

00:11:29.559 --> 00:11:31.340
to use this code on.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:35.419
So the next time we go to run this code, it works on the server and it works locally.

00:11:35.419 --> 00:11:37.940
It works on your machine and it works on my machine.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:41.859
And when we come back to this code in six months, it runs exactly like it's supposed

00:11:41.859 --> 00:11:42.859
to.

00:11:42.859 --> 00:11:45.260
It just works.

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:50.739
So again, with a little bit of effort and a bit of empathy for how other people are

00:11:50.739 --> 00:11:55.260
going to be interacting with the things you are creating in R, you can build a positive

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:56.260
interaction, right?

00:11:56.260 --> 00:12:01.020
A positive interaction with R or something you've created in R and kind of smooth out

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:07.780
those friction points that people run into and make things that just work for people.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:10.739
So the third principle is to promote growth.

00:12:10.739 --> 00:12:15.739
And we really want to bring as many people into the R fold and into the R community at

00:12:15.739 --> 00:12:17.700
our organization as possible.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:20.619
And so we do this in a couple of ways.

00:12:20.619 --> 00:12:25.500
The first that we do pretty often is have newer R users interact with existing scripts

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:26.780
and processes.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:33.140
So maybe a more advanced R user is going to write a script or some sort of process to

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:34.140
complete a task.

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:40.219
Maybe it's a data analysis, maybe it creates a table, maybe it creates a chart.

00:12:40.219 --> 00:12:44.700
And we can have newer users take that already written code and run it with maybe changes

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:50.780
to certain parameters or flags within that code.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:54.299
And this may lead to the following scenario.

00:12:54.299 --> 00:12:58.099
You're trying to figure out what exactly happened to the script that you wrote.

00:12:58.099 --> 00:13:03.739
So you ran lines 1 through 57, then you changed overwrite to true, then 61 through 66, then

00:13:03.739 --> 00:13:05.820
back to 37.

00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:11.659
And this can be a really kind of frustrating conversation to have for both people if you're

00:13:11.659 --> 00:13:15.780
trying to figure out exactly what happened and exactly what went wrong.

00:13:15.780 --> 00:13:19.580
And now the person interacting with this code who's maybe a newer R user is going to feel

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:22.460
frustrated and a little scared.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:27.140
So there's a couple of ways that you can just make this a little bit easier and provide

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:33.140
a more low-risk way for them to interact with this code.

00:13:33.140 --> 00:13:35.739
So one is you can use a dialog box.

00:13:35.739 --> 00:13:39.140
So something like the SVDialogs package.

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:44.979
You can write, again, one line of code, and you can have a user go run an R script, and

00:13:44.979 --> 00:13:49.960
when it gets to a certain point where you've inserted this dialog box code, a dialog box

00:13:49.960 --> 00:13:53.000
will pop up and give them the option to select yes or no.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.200
So maybe it's whether you're going to include a certain set of NAs or not.

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:00.479
Maybe it's whether you're going to run this for males or females.

00:14:00.479 --> 00:14:05.799
Whatever it is, it's a much easier way for them to interact with the code, and it's much

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:09.679
less likely that you're going to run into this tracking down what lines of code got

00:14:09.679 --> 00:14:12.919
run at what time and what order.

00:14:12.919 --> 00:14:17.440
So with a little more effort, you can also give them a more user-friendly interface to

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:18.440
interact with.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:26.640
So here's an example of a process where we have analysts run dozens of reports over a

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:30.960
couple of months each year, and we built a shiny dashboard for them.

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:35.039
So they can see what reports need to be run.

00:14:35.039 --> 00:14:37.239
There's some of this metadata here redacted.

00:14:37.239 --> 00:14:41.760
But how many reports are left to run, how many have already been run, and they can select

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:46.400
a specific report in the table and go to the details of that report, see all the metadata

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:50.760
that they need, and see all these action buttons that let them take certain steps in

00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:52.239
the process.

00:14:52.239 --> 00:15:00.479
So the users are interacting with buttons in this without actually having to run the

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:07.159
code themselves, and they're able to see exactly the products of this, these beautiful created

00:15:07.159 --> 00:15:12.359
R Markdown documents, without having to run the code themselves or dig into it.

00:15:12.359 --> 00:15:17.200
So a good example of how this can promote growth is we had an analyst start and say,

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:19.239
hey, I'm honestly not sure what happened.

00:15:19.239 --> 00:15:20.239
I caused this error.

00:15:20.239 --> 00:15:22.520
I thought I did everything right.

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:27.659
So I dug into it, figured out the error, fixed it, and got back to them.

00:15:27.659 --> 00:15:30.679
And they said, I'd really be interested in what went wrong.

00:15:30.679 --> 00:15:35.239
I really want to get better at using R. So I explained the process and what went wrong

00:15:35.239 --> 00:15:37.840
and why it was fixed now.

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:41.799
Cut to a few weeks later, and I get the following message after they hit an error.

00:15:41.799 --> 00:15:43.400
I'm looking at the log right now.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.960
So far, I only see warnings, but I'm going to go look for the error.

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:53.400
So now within the span of about a month, this person went from not having any idea how to

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:57.359
figure out what caused the error to digging into the logs themselves and trying to figure

00:15:57.359 --> 00:16:03.919
out what the error was and really kind of learning on their own and trying to get better.

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:08.200
So with a little bit of empathy and a little bit more effort maybe building out a whole

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:13.840
user interface, we've provided people a learning opportunity and a low-risk environment to

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:21.000
see how powerful R code can be and see how it runs without having to open the door to

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.119
maybe scary mistakes that they're not sure how to fix.

00:16:24.119 --> 00:16:29.520
So we can promote growth in users who may be interested in learning more.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:33.280
So what we want to leave you with today is to think about the question, how can you pollinate

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:36.520
your own data workflows using R?

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:38.460
So can you do no harm?

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:40.640
Can you make things that just work?

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:42.400
And can you promote growth?

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:49.359
And I would posit that you can, but thank you, thank you.

00:16:49.359 --> 00:16:51.119
But think about how you can be this bee, right?

00:16:51.119 --> 00:16:54.760
Think about how you can travel between different environments and work with different people

00:16:54.760 --> 00:17:00.700
and think about what you can learn from having empathy for the perspective of others and

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:05.800
think about what positive impact you can leave behind with you.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:06.760
So, thank you.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:08.380
**Applause**

